const a = [
  {"id":6854,"text":"A 30-year-old man is brought into the emergency as he has overdosed on an unknown drug. On examination, his pupils are pinpoint, nonreactive to light, his breathing is sighing and pre-regular in pattern, and his body is profusely sweating. What do you think based on these findings he has overdosed on?","explanation":null,"reference":"“Drug Effects on Eyes: Redness, Dilated \u0026 Pinpoint Pupils.” American Addiction Centers, https://americanaddictioncenters.org/health-complications-addiction/signs-drug-use-eyes. Accessed 21 Nov. 2023","responses":[{"text":"Milk of magnesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Naloxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Naphthalene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kerosene oil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Morphine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6868,"text":"Which type of fractures are seen with child abuse?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 333.","responses":[{"text":"Spalding fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greenstick fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nobbing fracture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buckle fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pathologic fractures","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6967,"text":"A dead body of a girl was brought for autopsy. On examination, she was pregnant, and severe injuries were observed in her pelvic area. On inquiry, her mother told that she tried to criminally induce abortion during which she died within minutes. What is the most probable cause of death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 340.","responses":[{"text":"Peritonitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagal inhibition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal Failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6971,"text":"An 11-year old boy presents with the complaint of swelling in his feet for the past 4 weeks. He is otherwise in good health and gives no previous history of any illness. Physical examination reveals pitting edema of the lower legs and a swollen abdomen. Urinalysis shows 4+ protein but no RBCs or WBCs.The treating physicians should consider which of the following conditions in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015:  917.","responses":[{"text":"Minimal change disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyelonephritis with acute tubular necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wilms tumor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7089,"text":"Which of the following regions of nephrons is most affected in toxin-mediated acute tubular necrosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collecting tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7418,"text":"What is the role of anti-diuretic hormone in the human body?","explanation":"**Anti-diuretic hormone (ADH)**, also known as vasopressin, plays a crucial role in regulating water balance in the human body.\r\n\r\nADH is produced in the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary gland in response to changes in blood osmolality and blood volume. Its primary function is to regulate water reabsorption in the kidneys and maintain the body's water balance.\r\n\r\nWhen blood osmolality increases (indicating higher solute concentration), or when blood volume decreases (indicating dehydration or reduced blood pressure), the hypothalamus senses these changes and releases ADH into the bloodstream. ADH then acts on the kidneys to increase water reabsorption in the collecting ducts. As a result, less water is excreted in urine, and more water is retained in the body, helping to restore normal blood osmolality and volume.\r\n\r\nConversely, when blood osmolality is low or blood volume is high, ADH secretion decreases, leading to increased water excretion in urine and maintaining proper water balance.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 939.","responses":[{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate water balance in the body","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7513,"text":"A 67-year-old male who is a known case of chronic renal failure (CRF) comes for his follow-up visit to the nephrologist. His creatinine is stable, however, his bicarbonate is 15 mEq/L. In order to prevent metabolic bone disease, his serum bicarbonate levels should be maintained at what level?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 418.","responses":[{"text":"\u003c40 others","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 25 mEq","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 21 mEq","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 21 mEq","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 10 mEq","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7610,"text":"A 30-year-old unmarried woman came to a doctor and requested her to induce an abortion. The doctor refused and told the women there is severe punishment for criminal abortion in Pakistan. What is the punishment of criminal abortion before babies' organs are formed in Pakistan?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan’s abortion provisions. Center for Reproductive Rights. Accessed November 3, 2022. https://reproductiverights.org/maps/provision/pakistans-abortion-provisions/","responses":[{"text":"3 years imprisonment if with consent","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1/20 diyat of the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 years imprisonment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Full diyat of the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 years imprisonment if without consent","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7634,"text":"A 27-year-old woman presents with complaints of an increased urinary frequency with dysuria for the past 4 days. A urinalysis reveals sp. gr. 1.014, pH 7.5, no glucose, no protein, no blood, nitrite positive, and many WBC's. She has a serum creatinine of 0.9 mg/dL. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 387.","responses":[{"text":"Cystitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary lithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lupus nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malakoplakia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urothelial carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7636,"text":"A fetus wrapped in an old newspaper was found in the garbage, brought by police to the medico-legal section for age determination. Haase's rule states what?","explanation":null,"reference":"Phillips B, Ong BB. “Was the infant born alive? ” a review of postmortem techniques used to determine live birth in cases of suspected neonaticide. Academic Forensic Pathology. 2018;8(4):874-893. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6491538/","responses":[{"text":"Crown Rump length of the fetus in cms gives age in months in 1st five month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Square root of crown rump length in cm gives age of fetus in 1st five months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crown rump length of fetus in inches gives age in months in 1st five months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Square root of crown-heel length in cm gives age of fetus in 1st five months","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crown heel length of the fetus in inches gives age in months in 1st five months","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7642,"text":"A child of 5 years was brought to ED, with multiple bruises of different ages the child is a case of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Battered child syndrome - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed October 24, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/battered-child-syndrome","responses":[{"text":"Sudden infant death syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Culpable homicide not amounting to murder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accidental injuries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Battered baby syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Act of omission by parents","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7740,"text":"Filicide is defined by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Resnick PJ. Filicide in the united states. Indian Journal of Psychiatry. Published December 2016. Accessed October 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5282617/","responses":[{"text":"Killing of a new born child by the parents","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Synonymous with criminal abortion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Killing of an illegitimate child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Killing of a disabled new born child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Killing of viable fetus inside the uterus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7754,"text":"A 30-year-old male presented, to the outpatient department with a high-grade fever and sore throat for the last 3 days. For one day he noticed blood in urine and facial puffiness. On examination, his blood pressure was 150/90mmHg with mild pedal and facial edema. What are the likely diagnoses?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 921.","responses":[{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lupus nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wegener's granulomatosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7881,"text":"A 6-month-old boy presented in emergency for high-grade fever. His blood CP results showed a high WBC count and CRP (C-reactive protein). Blood culture and urine culture confirmed the presence of E. coli. The physician came to the conclusion that the baby is suffering from a urinary tract infection that might be due to a congenital anomaly. Which one of the following is true related to congenital defects?","explanation":null,"reference":"Banker, Hiral, and Narothama R. Aeddula. “Vesicoureteral Reflux.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2023. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563262/.","responses":[{"text":"Vesico-ureteral reflux","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crossed fused renal ectopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Horse shoe kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multicystic dysplastic kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7902,"text":"A 55-year-old man presents with generalized edema and ascites. Laboratory tests show: a total serum protein of 5.2g/dl (range: 5.5-8.0g/dl), albumin of 1.9g/dl (range: 3.5-5.5g/dl), and serum cholesterol of 540mg/dl. 24-hour urine collection reveals 4.8gms of protein loss. Urine contains many hyaline casts but no RBCs or WBCs. Immuno-fluorescence on renal biopsy shows granular sub-epithelial deposits along the glomerular basement membranes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate glomerular pathology involved?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 912, 913.","responses":[{"text":"Minimal change disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous nephropathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasteurs syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8037,"text":"Before a transplant, the renal transplant team visits the patient to take consent about the procedure and also from the family after counseling. For valid consent, the patient should be which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Social","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mature","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Competent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confident","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8040,"text":"A 20-year-old man is brought into the emergency room after a morphine overdose.  Upon examination, he is unconscious, pupils are pinpoint and non-reactive. Several injection marks are seen on his arms. What is the immediate treatment after maintaining the airway, breathing, and circulation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Naloxone with pethidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Naloxone with gastric lavage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric lavage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Naloxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric lavage with tannic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8041,"text":"In Pakistan, on which grounds is abortion justifiable?","explanation":null,"reference":"“Pakistan’s Abortion Provisions.” Center for Reproductive Rights, https://reproductiverights.org/maps/provision/pakistans-abortion-provisions/. Accessed 17 Nov. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Humanitarian grounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Social grounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eugenic grounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic grounds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Threatened","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8085,"text":"During the first three months, what is the best-skilled method of termination of pregnancy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 35.","responses":[{"text":"Electricity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vaccum aspiration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abortion stick","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8094,"text":"A 22-year-old woman presents with swelling of the legs. On urinalysis, there was increased proteinuria. She is diagnosed to have tubulointerstitial nephritis. It could have been drug-induced. It is characterized by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Increased urinary sugar level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appearance of symptoms after about two weeks of exposure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased blood urea nitrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dose dependent severity of the disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased glomerular filtration rate and oliguria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8100,"text":"A graduate student is planning to make a high-altitude climb in South America while on vacation. He will not have time to acclimate slowly to the altitude. What drug is useful in preventing high-altitude sickness?","explanation":null,"reference":"Paralikar, Swapnil J., and Jagdish H. Paralikar. “High-Altitude Medicine.” Indian Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine, 2010, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2923424/.","responses":[{"text":"Amiloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Desmopressin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethacrynic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demeclocycline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":8148,"text":"A 9-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with complaints of cola-colored urine. He has a past history of being treated for a sore throat infection 3 weeks ago. His blood pressure is 145/95 mmHg. Urinalysis reveals red cell casts. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasture's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alport syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous glomerulopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8371,"text":"One of the signs of remote delivery in the living women is the presence of linea nigra a dark line of pigmentation in what location?","explanation":null,"reference":"Vora, Rita V., et al. “Pregnancy and Skin.” Journal of Family Medicine and Primary Care, vol. 3, no. 4, 2014, pp. 318–24. PubMed Central, https://doi.org/10.4103/2249-4863.148099.","responses":[{"text":"From umbilicus to ensiform cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"From pubis to ensiform cartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Around umbilicus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"From pubis to umbilicus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper part of thigh","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8372,"text":"A post mortem examination was conducted on a 38-year-old parous woman to see the signs of remote delivery, what are the findings that would confirm the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 362.","responses":[{"text":"The external os is vertical irregular and admit 2 fingers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The internal os is soft, patulous, rounded with a dimple in the center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The top of fundus is at a lower level than that of broad ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The walls of a uterus are concave from inside forming a wider and rounded cavity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The cervix and body of uterus are about the same length","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8382,"text":"Two infants in different stages of development may be born in which of the following conditions?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 359.","responses":[{"text":"Superfecundation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superfoetation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heterozygotic twins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectopic pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Homologous artificial insemination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8645,"text":"A patient presented with the complaint of recurrent stones despite drinking adequate water. Which of the following is the most common renal stone?","explanation":null,"reference":"Thakore, Palak, and Terrence H. Liang. “Urolithiasis.” StatPearls [Internet], StatPearls Publishing, 2023. www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559101/.","responses":[{"text":"Magnesium ammonium phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium oxalate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cysteine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8646,"text":"Which of the following is the appropriate drug of choice for a patient having renal calcium calculi?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Verapamil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochlorothiazide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbapenem","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8649,"text":"Calculate the net filtration pressure if the value of capillary pressure is 60 mm H2O, glomerular oncotic pressure is 32 mm H2O, and bowman hydrostatic pressure is 18 mm H2O.","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"15 mm H2O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 mm H2O","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0 mm H2O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 mm H2O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 mm H2O","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8764,"text":"Spalding sign is a characteristic finding of which of the following condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 328.","responses":[{"text":"Unborn baby in the uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrauterine dead fetus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abortion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maceration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8861,"text":"Which of the following is the characteristic difference between a false virgin and a true virgin?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Wide vaginal wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Funnel shaped vagina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non rugosity of vaginal wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hymen edges undulated plus 2 fingers inserted","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Narrow vagina","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10867,"text":"Which type of statistical test is commonly used if the sample size is below 30, to determine whether the mean of a population significantly differs from a specific value or from the mean of another population and to determine whether the difference is statistically significant?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lani, James. “T-Test.” Statistics Solutions, 12 Nov. 2009, https://www.statisticssolutions.com/t-test/.","responses":[{"text":"Anova","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Logistic regression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Linear regression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chi square","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10871,"text":"A 10-year-old male is brought to the clinic by his parents with complaints of periorbital puffiness and pedal edema. His urine analysis shows proteinuria, absence of RBCs and casts. You suspect minimal change disease. What would the renal biopsy findings in this patient be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 914.","responses":[{"text":"Dense deposits on subepithelial surface of basement membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal light microscopy and immunofluorescence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sclerosis of segments of some glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased IgA deposition in mesangium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescent formation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10881,"text":"An 85-year-old male is diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma. Regarding this, all of the following statements are true except?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"It is more common in men","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In 25 percent of cases, there are no local symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Following radical nephrectomy, radiotherapy should be given","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound and tri-phasic CT urography are imaging methods of choice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A left sided varicocele may be a presenting feature in males","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10882,"text":"A 45-year-old lady is booked for a cholecystectomy. During her preoperative workup, radiological investigations reveal multiple cystic dilations of the collecting ducts in the renal medulla. No cortical scarring is present and renal function is normal. What is the most likely cause of these findings?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 948.","responses":[{"text":"Medullary sponge kidney","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubulo-interstitial nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Childhood polycystic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adult polycystic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephronophthisis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10883,"text":"A 6-year-old child undergoes surgical exploration and nephrectomy for a suspected kidney tumor. His ultrasound shows an enlarged multicystic, irregular left kidney. Biopsy shows no tumor. However, there are islands of undifferentiated mesenchyme and cartilage. Which of the following is correct regarding this disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 949.","responses":[{"text":"Inherited disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excellent prognosis after nephrectomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Commonest genetic cause of end stage renal disease in children","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary ciliopathy implicated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is rarely associated with other lower urinary tract anomalies","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12300,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to be filtered from glomerular capillaries?","explanation":null,"reference":"Glomerular filtration barrier - an overview | Sciencedirect topics. Accessed October 25, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/glomerular-filtration-barrier","responses":[{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12345,"text":"Rapid correction of hyponatremia may cause which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kleinschmidt-DeMasters BK, Norenberg MD. Rapid correction of hyponatremia causes demyelination: relation to central pontine myelinolysis. Science. 1981;211(4486):1068-1070. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7466381/","responses":[{"text":"Heart attack","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain herniation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central pontine myelinolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroke","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12346,"text":"Which of the following is the most common organism responsible for causing nephritic syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 909, 914.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta hemolytic streptococci","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12351,"text":"Sexual enjoyment from inflicting pain on others as well as on oneself is called which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Definition of Algolagnia. Accessed November 6, 2022. https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/algolagnia","responses":[{"text":"Sadism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Satyriasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masochism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beastiality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Algolagnia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12355,"text":"According to World Health Organization (WHO), drug dependence is defined as which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"ICD-10 Classification of Mental and Behavioural Disorders Clinical descriptions and diagnostic guidelines. Accessed November 6, 2022. https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9241544228","responses":[{"text":"Intoxication with harmful effects on society","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intoxication with harmful effects on himself","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No withdrawal symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Desire to take drug repeatedly and increase the doses","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic and periodic intoxication with harmful effects on himself and society","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13286,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to be seen in nephrotic syndrome?","explanation":"Nephrotic syndrome is characterized by a set of clinical and laboratory findings:\r\n\r\n1. *Heavy proteinuria*: Typically exceeding 3.5 grams per day.\r\n2. *Hypoalbuminemia*: As a result of the significant loss of albumin in the urine.\r\n3. *Decreased plasma colloid osmotic pressure*: Due to the loss of albumin, leading to edema.\r\n4. *Selective proteinuria*: Initially, there's a loss of primarily albumin, making it \"selective\". Over time, it can become non-selective with the loss of other plasma proteins.\r\n\r\n*Hematuria*, on the other hand, is the presence of red blood cells in the urine. While it can be seen in nephritic syndrome (which is a different renal pathology), it is not a typical feature of nephrotic syndrome and is therefore the least likely to be observed among the options provided.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 911.","responses":[{"text":"Hematuria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heavy proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased plasma colloid osmotic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selective proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoalbuminemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13296,"text":"A patient presents to the emergency room with complaints of diarrhea and vomiting for one day. He is semi-conscious and severely dehydrated. What is the first-line management in this patient?","explanation":"In a severely dehydrated patient who is semi-conscious, the primary concern is restoring fluid balance and preventing complications like shock or organ damage. \r\n\r\nThe most effective and immediate way to manage severe dehydration, especially in a patient with altered consciousness, is **IV fluid replacement**. This approach allows for rapid rehydration and correction of electrolyte imbalances. Intravenous access facilitates the quick delivery of fluids, bypassing the gastrointestinal tract, which can be compromised in the context of diarrhea and vomiting.\r\n\r\nOral fluid replacement is typically reserved for milder cases where the patient is alert and can drink. Antibiotics, whether oral or IV, would be considered based on the suspected underlying cause (e.g., bacterial infection), but fluid replacement remains the immediate priority.","reference":"Taylor K, Jones EB. Adult dehydration. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555956/","responses":[{"text":"Oral fluid replacement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"KYB diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV fluid replacement","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13319,"text":"A 55-year-old male with COPD presents to the clinic with increased severity of shortness of breath. His immediate arterial blood gases show respiratory acidosis. What is the first step in the interpretation of arterial blood gases?","explanation":"When interpreting arterial blood gases (ABGs), the initial step is to assess the pH of the blood. The pH will provide an immediate clue as to whether the primary disturbance is acidemia or alkalemia. If the pH is lower than the reference range (usually \u003c7.35), it indicates acidemia, while if it's higher (usually \u003e7.45), it indicates alkalemia. After determining the pH, the next steps involve evaluating PaCO₂ and HCO₃ levels to discern whether the primary disturbance is respiratory or metabolic in nature. For a patient with COPD presenting with worsening symptoms, respiratory acidosis (elevated PaCO₂) is a common finding. However, the starting point for ABG interpretation always remains the pH.","reference":"ood P, Paul G, Puri S. Interpretation of arterial blood gas. Indian Journal of Critical Care Medicine : Peer-reviewed, Official Publication of Indian Society of Critical Care Medicine. Published 2010. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2936733/","responses":[{"text":"Anion gap","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH of blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HCO₃ level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaCO₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta-delta gap","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13630,"text":"A group of students was analyzing their research data set. The data showed that the frequency distribution of age of the study participants had a long tail on the right-hand side of the curve than on the left side. Compared to the median value, where does the mean value lie on the frequency distribution?","explanation":"In a frequency distribution with a long tail on the right-hand side (**positively skewed distribution**), the mean value is typically higher (greater) than the median value. This is because the presence of extreme values (outliers) on the right-hand side of the distribution, in the long tail, pulls the **mean** in that direction, making it **higher than the median**.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 265.","responses":[{"text":"In the center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Higher","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Smaller","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"On the left side","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13631,"text":"A researcher wants to find the difference between the mean hemoglobin levels of two patient groups. The groups to compare are smokers and non-smokers. What would be the test of significance that can be applied to compare these groups?","explanation":"The **independent sample student t-test** is specifically designed for comparing the **means of two independent groups**. In this case, smokers and non-smokers are two separate, independent groups of patients.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe chi-square test is used for analyzing categorical data, not continuous variables like hemoglobin levels.\r\n\r\nOne sample student t-test is used when you want to compare the mean of a single sample to a known population mean, not for comparing two independent groups.\r\n\r\nPaired student's t-test is used when you have two related groups and want to assess changes within the same group over time, which is not the case here.\r\n\r\nFisher exact test is used for analyzing categorical data when dealing with small sample sizes, not for comparing the means of continuous variables like hemoglobin levels.","reference":"Kim TK. T test as a parametric statistic. Korean Journal of Anesthesiology. Published December 2015. Accessed December 17, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4667138/","responses":[{"text":"Chi-square test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fisher exact test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Independent sample student t-test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"One sample student t-test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paired students t-test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13632,"text":"A professor while analyzing the data of one thousand covid-19 hospitalized patients noted that the average C-reactive protein values of patients before and during the illness were 26.2 mg/L and 46.5 mg/L, respectively. To assess if there is a significant difference between the recorded C-reactive protein values, which of the following tests will be applied?","explanation":"The **paired student's t-test** is specifically designed to compare the **means of two related groups** (in this case, CRP values before and during the illness) to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between them. It takes into account the paired nature of the data and is suitable for assessing changes within the same group of subjects over time.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCorrelation analysis is used to measure the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two continuous variables, but it does not assess the difference in means.\r\n\r\nThe chi-square test is used for analyzing categorical data, not continuous variables like CRP values.\r\n\r\nIndependent sample student t-test is used to compare the means of two independent (unrelated) groups, which is not the case here as you are comparing the same group before and during illness.\r\n\r\nOne sample student t-test is used when you want to compare the mean of a single sample to a known population mean, not for comparing two related groups.","reference":"Kim TK. T test as a parametric statistic. Korean Journal of Anesthesiology. Published December 2015. Accessed December 17, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4667138/","responses":[{"text":"Independent sample student t-test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chi-square test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Correlation analysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paired students t-test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"One sample student t-test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13633,"text":"While conducting a data analysis you come across an extreme value in your data set. Which one of the following measures of central tendency/variance is suitable to summarize data and is least affected by extreme values in the data set?","explanation":"The **median** is the **middle value** of a data set when it is ordered, and it is not influenced by extreme values since it considers the position of the data points rather than their actual values.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe mean is heavily influenced by extreme values because it takes into account the actual values of all data points.\r\n\r\nThe mode represents the most frequently occurring value in a data set and does not necessarily provide a good summary of the central tendency, especially when extreme values are present.\r\n\r\nThe range is a measure of the spread or dispersion of the data, and it does not summarize the central tendency.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 265.","responses":[{"text":"Mode","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arithmetic mean","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Range","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13635,"text":"A 10-year-old boy presents with features of nephritic syndrome following infection with streptococcal pharyngitis. Physical examination reveals facial edema. His blood pressure is 180/110 mmHg. A 24-hour urine collection test demonstrates oliguria and urinalysis shows hematuria. What finding in his urinalysis would suggest that the hematuria is caused by kidney involvement and not by bleeding from the urinary bladder?","explanation":"The presence of **red blood cell casts** indicates that red blood cells are being cast within the renal tubules and then excreted in the urine. This finding is a hallmark of **glomerular bleeding** and suggests that the source of hematuria is within the kidneys.\r\n\r\nThe patient's presentation of nephritic syndrome following streptococcal pharyngitis is suggestive of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (PSGN), a type of glomerulonephritis that occurs as a result of an immune response to a recent streptococcal infection. PSGN often presents with hematuria and proteinuria, along with other features of nephritic syndrome.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemoglobin crystals may be seen in conditions where there is intravascular hemolysis but are not specific to kidney involvement.\r\n\r\nWhite blood cell casts are more indicative of inflammation or infection in the renal tubules rather than glomerular bleeding.\r\n\r\nPhagocytosed hemoglobin would be unlikely to appear in urinalysis.\r\n\r\nBlood clots would suggest bleeding from the urinary bladder or another lower urinary tract source, not glomerular bleeding.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 910.","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin crystals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood clots","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells casts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"White blood cells casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytosed hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13638,"text":"An 8-year-old boy becomes increasingly lethargic. On physical examination, he has swelling in his legs and ankles. Urinalysis shows 4+ proteinuria and no blood or glucose. 24-hour urine protein loss is 3.8 g. Immunofluorescence microscopy of renal biopsy is unremarkable. The child's condition improves after a course of corticosteroid therapy. Which of the following morphologic alteration is most likely to be responsible for his condition?","explanation":"**Minimal change disease** (MCD) is a common cause of nephrotic syndrome in **children** and is characterized by selective proteinuria with no immune complex deposits visible under immunofluorescence microscopy. The **loss of the negatively charged foot processes in podocytes** leads to increased permeability of the glomerular filtration barrier to proteins, causing proteinuria. The loss of albumin in the urine leads to edema, which manifests as swelling in the legs and ankles.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nEpimembranous IgG deposits are seen in membranous nephropathy.\r\n\r\nMesangial immune-complex deposits are associated with mesangial proliferative glomerulonephritis, which typically presents differently and is not consistent with the clinical and histological findings described.\r\n\r\nSubepithelial and subendothelial IgG deposits are characteristic of membraneoproliferative glomerulonephritis, which doesn't match the presentation in this case.\r\n\r\nThickening of the capillary basement membrane is seen in diabetic nephropathy and Alport Syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 914.","responses":[{"text":"Epimembranous IgG deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subepithelial and subendothelial IgG deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesangial immune-complex deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thickening of capillary basement membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Effacement of podocyte foot processes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13641,"text":"Which of the following is most commonly associated with HIV infection?","explanation":"**Focal segmental glomerulonephritis** is frequently seen in patients with an **HIV** infection and can lead to significant renal impairment. However, it is important to note that the association of HIV infection with glomerular diseases can vary by geographical location and patient population.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMembranoproliferative glomerulonephritis and membranous glomerulonephritis can also occur in HIV-infected patients but are less common compared to focal segmental glomerulonephritis.\r\n\r\nLupus nephritis is not directly related to HIV infection but is associated with systemic lupus erythematosus.\r\n\r\nMinimal change disease is relatively uncommon in the context of HIV infection.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 915.","responses":[{"text":"Membranous glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lupus nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal segmental glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimal change disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13697,"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis is an immunologically mediated disease. Which of the following is the classic diagnostic microscopic picture of this disease?","explanation":"**Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis** (PSGN) is an immunologically mediated kidney disease that occurs as a result of a prior streptococcal infection, most commonly a streptococcal throat infection or skin infection.\r\n\r\nThe glomeruli in PSGN are often larger than normal due to swelling and an increased number of cells within the glomeruli, including mesangial cells and inflammatory cells.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 908.","responses":[{"text":"Enlarged and hypercellular glomeruli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercellular glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukocyte infiltration in glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescent formation in glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13698,"text":"Which of the following glomerular disorders is a cause of nephritic syndrome in adults?","explanation":"**IgA nephropathy**, a common cause of nephritic syndrome in adults, is characterized by the deposition of immunoglobulin A (IgA) in the glomeruli. It can present with hematuria, proteinuria, and varying degrees of renal impairment, which are characteristic features of nephritic syndrome.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nFocal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) is more typically associated with nephrotic syndrome, characterized by heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidemia, and edema.\r\n\r\nWhile crescentic glomerulonephritis can present with nephritic syndrome, it's usually more aggressive and rapidly progressive. It is often considered under the broader category of rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN).\r\n\r\nLipoid nephrosis is another term for minimal change disease, which is a common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children.\r\n\r\nMembranous glomerulopathy is typically associated with nephrotic syndrome due to significant proteinuria.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 920-921.","responses":[{"text":"Lipoid nephrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous glomerulopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescenteric glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13699,"text":"Which of the following conditions is the most important cause of hydronephrosis?","explanation":"When **urine flow is obstructed**, it backs up into the kidney, leading to increased pressure within the renal pelvis and calyces. This pressure can result in the dilation and swelling of the affected kidney, causing **hydronephrosis**.\r\n\r\nObstruction to urine flow can occur at different levels within the urinary tract, such as at the level of the renal pelvis, ureter, or bladder outlet. Causes of obstruction can include kidney stones, ureteral strictures, benign prostatic hyperplasia (in males), congenital anomalies, tumors, and other conditions that impede the normal flow of urine.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile urinary tract infections, renal tumors, tuberculosis, and congenital anomalies, can contribute to or complicate hydronephrosis, obstruction to outflow of urine is the primary and most important cause of this condition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 945.","responses":[{"text":"Urinary tract infections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal tumors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital anomalies of the kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstruction to outflow of urine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13708,"text":"Linear deposition of IgG on the basement membrane is seen in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"**Goodpasture syndrome**, also known as anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) disease, is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of autoantibodies, specifically IgG antibodies, that target the basement membranes of both the lung and kidney glomeruli.\r\n\r\nIn Goodpasture syndrome, these **IgG antibodies** bind **linearly** to the basement membrane, leading to an inflammatory response, pulmonary hemorrhage, and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 910.","responses":[{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shunt nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasture syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13709,"text":"A patient presents with hemoptysis, renal failure, and anti-basement membrane antibodies. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Goodpasture syndrome**, also known as anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) disease, is a rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of antibodies directed against the basement membranes of both the lung and kidney glomeruli. This condition can lead to pulmonary hemorrhage (hemoptysis) and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, resulting in renal failure.\r\n\r\nThe **anti-basement membrane antibodies** in Goodpasture syndrome specifically target the type IV collagen in the basement membranes of the lungs and kidneys.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile other autoimmune diseases like Wegener granulomatosis, Henoch-Schönlein purpura, and Churg-Strauss syndrome can also involve the lungs and kidneys to varying degrees, the presence of anti-basement membrane antibodies is most strongly associated with Goodpasture syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 704.","responses":[{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Churg-Strauss syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Henoch-Schönlein purpura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasture syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Wegener granulomatosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13710,"text":"Which renal calculi are common in diseases having rapid cell turnover?","explanation":"**Uric acid** stones are composed mainly of uric acid, which is a product of **purine metabolism**. When there is **rapid cell turnover**, as seen in conditions like leukemia, lymphoma, or tumor lysis syndrome, there is an increased production of uric acid. The excess uric acid can lead to the formation of uric acid stones in the kidneys. These stones can obstruct the urinary tract and cause kidney stones.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 947.","responses":[{"text":"Oxalate stones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium oxalate stones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium ammonium phosphate stones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid stones","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystine stones","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13716,"text":"Patients with diabetes mellitus have urine with which of the following characteristics?","explanation":"Glucose in the urine is referred to as glycosuria. When a person with **diabetes** has elevated blood glucose levels, the excess glucose is transported to the renal tubules, and the renal threshold for glucose is exceeded. This results in **glucose** being excreted in the **urine**.\r\n\r\nThe presence of glucose in the urine causes an **increase in urine volume** (polyuria) because glucose in the urine carries water with it through osmosis. This leads to increased urine output.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the high glucose content in the urine contributes to an **increased specific gravity**. Specific gravity measures the concentration of solutes in the urine, and when there is a higher concentration of glucose, it increases the specific gravity of the urine.","reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2019: 167.\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 367.","responses":[{"text":"Same volume and same specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased volume and decreased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased volume and decreased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased volume and increased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased volume and increased specific gravity","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13723,"text":"A 17-year-old girl decided to go on a starvation diet. After 1 week of starving herself, which of the following substances would most likely be found in her urine?","explanation":"During periods of **starvation** or fasting, the body's primary source of energy shifts from glucose to fat metabolism. When the body breaks down fats for energy, it produces ketone bodies as a byproduct. **Ketones**, such as acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate, are water-soluble compounds that can be excreted in the urine.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 858.","responses":[{"text":"Blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ketones","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13725,"text":"In a patient with severe dehydration, which of the following organs most commonly becomes non-functional almost immediately?","explanation":"**Dehydration** is a condition characterized by the excessive loss of body fluids, typically through vomiting, diarrhea, excessive sweating, or inadequate fluid intake. It can lead to a decrease in blood volume and, subsequently, reduced blood flow to various organs. While other organs may also be affected by severe dehydration, the kidneys are particularly vulnerable and can become non-functional almost immediately when there is a severe depletion of body fluids.\r\n\r\n**Acute kidney injury** can occur relatively quickly in cases of severe dehydration. This can result in electrolyte imbalances, metabolic acidosis, and the accumulation of waste products in the bloodstream.","reference":"Roncal-Jimenez C, Lanaspa MA, Jensen T, Sanchez-Lozada LG, Johnson RJ. Mechanisms by which dehydration may lead to chronic kidney disease. Annals of Nutrition and Metabolism. Published 2015. Accessed December 18, 2022. https://www.karger.com/Article/FullText/381239","responses":[{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eyes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidneys","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13726,"text":"A 15-year-old girl with no known prior comorbidities presented to the emergency department with abdominal pain, vomiting, and shortness of breath for one day. She has mild tenderness in her epigastrium. She is dehydrated and hypotensive. Her blood sugar level is 450 mg/dL. What is the most common cause of a high anion gap metabolic acidosis?","explanation":"**Diabetic ketoacidosis** (DKA) is a life-threatening complication of uncontrolled diabetes mellitus, particularly in individuals with type 1 diabetes. It is characterized by severe **hyperglycemia***, ketosis, and metabolic acidosis.\r\n\r\nDKA is associated with a **high anion gap metabolic acidosis**, which is characterized by an increased concentration of unmeasured anions in the blood, primarily ketones. The metabolic acidosis leads to symptoms such as abdominal pain, vomiting, shortness of breath, and dehydration, which are consistent with this patient's presentation.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 631.","responses":[{"text":"Diabetic ketoacidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salicylate poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methanol poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethanol poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal tubular acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13727,"text":"Which of the following functions is the kidney not responsible for?","explanation":"**Cortisol** is a steroid hormone produced by the **adrenal glands** and plays a significant role in various physiological processes, including the regulation of metabolism, immune response, and stress response.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRemoving waste products from the blood through the process of filtration and excretion.\r\n\r\nSecreting renin, which is involved in regulating blood pressure and maintaining fluid balance.\r\n\r\nPlaying a crucial role in the regulation of blood pressure through mechanisms like the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.\r\n\r\nActivating vitamin D, which is important for calcium absorption and bone health.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 955.","responses":[{"text":"Cortisol production","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Removing waste products from blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secreting renin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Regulation of blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activating vitamin D","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13729,"text":"What may patients with renal failure present with?","explanation":"Renal failure can lead to fluid overload and pulmonary edema, resulting in difficulty breathing.\r\n\r\nRenal failure can cause the accumulation of waste products and toxins in the body, leading to gastrointestinal symptoms like nausea and vomiting.\r\n\r\nReduced urine output or oliguria is a common feature of acute or chronic renal failure.\r\n\r\nRenal failure can disrupt the balance of electrolytes in the body, leading to imbalances in sodium, potassium, calcium, and other electrolytes, which can have various clinical manifestations.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 897. \r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 588-589.","responses":[{"text":"Electrolyte disturbance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nausea and vomiting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased urine output","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shortness of breath","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13730,"text":"A 17-year-old boy came presents to the clinic with recurrent hematuria for the past 3 months. He also states that he feels febrile and has a mild body ache. On examination, there is no anemia, edema, congested throat, or organomegaly. There is no similar personal or family history of a similar illness and no other chronic illnesses. Initial investigations reveal normal hemoglobin, albumin, urea, creatinine, and alanine aminotransferase. A urine drug report shows grade-1 parenchymal changes. During an autoimmune workup, the presence of anti-nuclear antibodies was positive, and 2+ fine speckled with normal anti-ds-DNA and complement levels. What should be the next appropriate investigation to establish a diagnosis?","explanation":"Recurrent hematuria, febrile episodes, mild body aches, and positive findings on autoimmune workup (positive anti-nuclear antibodies and 2+ fine speckled pattern) with normal anti-ds-DNA and complement levels suggest a potential autoimmune or immune-mediated kidney condition.\r\n\r\n**Kidney biopsy** is often considered the gold standard for diagnosing and characterizing various kidney diseases, especially when there is suspicion of **glomerulonephritis** or **parenchymal changes**. It allows for the examination of kidney tissue under a microscope, which can provide crucial information about the underlying cause of hematuria and other renal abnormalities.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nUrine culture and sensitivity are typically performed to rule out urinary tract infections, but in this case, the presence of autoimmune markers and parenchymal changes indicates a need for further investigation beyond infection screening.\r\n\r\nCT-pyelogram may be useful for imaging the urinary tract but may not provide specific information about the underlying kidney pathology.\r\n\r\nAntineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA) testing is generally associated with conditions such as vasculitis, which can affect the kidneys but may not be the primary diagnostic test for the presented symptoms.\r\n\r\nUrinary calcium may help evaluate conditions related to calcium metabolism but is less likely to provide a definitive diagnosis for the described clinical presentation.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 566.","responses":[{"text":"Urinary calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT-pyelogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine culture and sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13731,"text":"A 4-year-old boy of weight 15 kg who is a known case of steroid dependent nephrotic syndrome presents to you with complaints of fever and flu like symptoms for the past 3 days. The child is currently in remission and receiving alternate day prednisone. What is the most appropriate management for this child's current problem?","explanation":"When a child with **nephrotic syndrome** develops an **intercurrent infection**, it is common practice to temporarily increase the dose of corticosteroids to provide additional anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive effects to manage the flare-up associated with the infection.\r\n\r\nThe appropriate management in this situation is to **treat the infection** and to shift the **prednisone** dose from alternate days to **daily** at the same dose for **2 weeks**. This helps provide optimal control of the disease during the infection and reduces the risk of relapse.\r\n\r\nOnce the infection is resolved, the prednisone dose can be tapered back to the previous alternate-day regimen.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Pediatrics, Topic: Nephrotic and Nephritic Syndrome, Sub-topic: Therapy for Frequently Relapsing (FR) and Steroid-dependent (SD) SNSS.","responses":[{"text":"Treat infection, continue prednisone and add steroid sparing agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat infection and continue alternate day prednisone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat infection and restart prednisone in full daily divided doses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat infection and shift prednisone same dose to daily dosage instead of alternate days for 2 weeks","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Home remedies for flu and restart full dose prednisone on alternate days","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13732,"text":"A 3-year-old boy was diagnosed to have nephrotic syndrome roughly 6 months back. He went into complete remission within one week of starting oral prednisone therapy but relapsed soon afterward during therapy. He later relapsed again a few days back. What will be the most appropriate categorization of his disease?","explanation":"When a patient with nephrotic syndrome experiences two consecutive relapses during corticosteroid therapy, or within 14 days of ceasing therapy, despite initially responding to steroid therapy, they are classified as having **steroid-dependent** nephrotic syndrome.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Pediatrics, Topic: Nephrotic and Nephritic Syndrome, Sub-topic: Definitions.","responses":[{"text":"Infrequently relapsing nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroid sensitive nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroid dependent nephrotic syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroid resistant nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frequently relapsing nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13733,"text":"A 60-year-old patient has a clinical history of frequent episodes of renal colic with calcium-containing stones. His clinical workup indicates that he has a defect in proximal tubular calcium reabsorption. Which of the following diuretic agent is most useful in the treatment of recurrent calcium stones?","explanation":"Thiazide diuretics, like **chlorthalidone**, are known to decrease the urinary excretion of calcium by promoting its reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule of the nephron. This reduction in urinary calcium excretion can help **prevent** the formation of **calcium-containing kidney stones**, particularly those associated with hypercalciuria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSpironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic and is not typically used for the prevention of calcium stones. It is more commonly used in conditions where potassium retention is desired.\r\n\r\nDiazoxide is primarily used to treat certain medical conditions, such as hypoglycemia and hypertensive emergencies.\r\n\r\nMannitol is an osmotic diuretic used to increase urine output and reduce intracranial or intraocular pressure. \r\n\r\nEthacrynic acid is a loop diuretic used for conditions like edema and heart failure.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 138.","responses":[{"text":"Mannitol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethacrynic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diazoxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13734,"text":"A male patient was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis. The hepatologist prescribed loop diuretics to treat his ascites. Which of the following is an important pharmacological effect of chronic therapy with loop diuretics?","explanation":"**Loop diuretics**, such as furosemide, can lead to **metabolic alkalosis**. This occurs because of the increased excretion of chloride ions due to diuretic action in the loop of Henle, which can lead to an imbalance in the acid-base homeostasis in the body. Additionally, the loss of potassium in the urine can cause the kidneys to excrete more hydrogen ions, further contributing to alkalosis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics typically decrease blood pressure by reducing blood volume and venous pressure, not increasing it.\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics increase the excretion of calcium in urine.\r\n\r\nWhile diuretics should be used cautiously in pregnancy, they are not primarily known for teratogenic effects. This caution is more related to concerns about volume and electrolyte balance in the mother and fetus.\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics are often used to reduce pulmonary vascular pressure, particularly in conditions like heart failure.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 137.","responses":[{"text":"Increase in pulmonary vascular pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teratogenic effect in pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased urinary excretion of calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13735,"text":"A 45-year-old male patient was brought to an emergency medical room with a history of a road traffic accident. Both a clinical examination and a CT scan confirmed the presence of a head injury with cerebral edema. Which of the following diuretics would be most useful for his condition?","explanation":"**Mannitol** is an osmotic diuretic commonly used in the treatment of **cerebral edema**, particularly in cases of head injury and increased intracranial pressure (ICP). It works by drawing water out of brain cells and reducing cerebral edema, thereby helping to decrease intracranial pressure.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nOther diuretics like furosemide, chlorthalidone, and spironolactone may have different mechanisms of action and are not typically used as the primary treatment for cerebral edema.\r\n\r\nAcetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that can also reduce intracranial pressure to some extent, but it is not as commonly used as mannitol in the acute management of cerebral edema.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 140.","responses":[{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mannitol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13736,"text":"Which of the following is not an established side-effect of loop diuretics?","explanation":"Loop diuretics, such as furosemide, are medications commonly used to increase the excretion of salt and water by the kidneys. They are primarily used to treat conditions like edema and hypertension. **Hyperglycemia** is **not** typically associated with the use of **loop diuretics**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics can lead to the loss of potassium from the body, which can result in low potassium levels in the blood.\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics can cause a reduction in blood volume, leading to hypovolemia.\r\n\r\nLoop diuretics can lead to low sodium levels in the blood, a condition known as hyponatremia.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, particularly with high doses or rapid intravenous administration, loop diuretics can have a side effect on the ear, leading to potential ototoxicity and hearing problems.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 137-138.","responses":[{"text":"Hypovolemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ototoxicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13737,"text":"\"Rape\" is a natural sexual offense. What section is it charged under?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 367.","responses":[{"text":"377 PPC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"375 PPC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"420 PPC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"376 PPC","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"497 PPC","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13738,"text":"What is sexual intercourse by a man with a woman who is related to him by a blood relation termed as?","explanation":"**Incest** refers to **sexual activity** or intercourse between individuals who are closely related by blood, such as siblings (brothers and sisters) or between other close **blood relatives**. In many cultures and legal systems, incest is considered taboo and is often illegal due to concerns about genetic risks and social norms.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRape is non-consensual sexual activity involving one person forcing another person to engage in sexual intercourse or other sexual acts without their consent.\r\n\r\nAdultery refers to the act of a married person engaging in sexual relations with someone other than their spouse.\r\n\r\nFornication generally refers to consensual sexual intercourse between two individuals who are not married to each other.\r\n\r\nZina is a term used in Islamic law to refer to unlawful sexual intercourse or extramarital sexual relations.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 385.","responses":[{"text":"Adultery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rape","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fornication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incest","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13743,"text":"A 19-year-old unmarried female with a history of alleged kidnapping and rape was brought to the medicolegal office for examination. On genital examination, vulval bruising and torn fourchette hymen were seen. Ideally, what is the most common site of rupture of the hymen?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 376.","responses":[{"text":"3 and 9 o'clock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 and 7 o'clock","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"11 and 2 o'clock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 and 12 o'clock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4 and 7 o'clock","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13746,"text":"What is the probable sign of pregnancy corresponding to around 6-8 weeks, where the lower uterine segment becomes soft and compressible known as?","explanation":"**Hegar's sign** is a physical finding that can be observed during a pelvic examination in early pregnancy, typically around **6-8 weeks gestation**. It involves the **softening** and compressibility of the **lower uterine segment**. This change is due to hormonal and structural changes in the uterus as it prepares to accommodate the growing fetus.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBallottement is observed later in pregnancy (usually in the second trimester) where the examiner can feel a rebound or floating sensation when gently tapping the uterine wall. It is used to detect the presence of the fetus and is not typically observed as early as 6-8 weeks.\r\n\r\nGoodell's sign is the softening of the cervix that can occur in early pregnancy. It is not specific to the lower uterine segment and does not involve compressibility.\r\n\r\nJacquemier's sign refers to the bluish discoloration of the vagina during pregnancy.\r\n\r\nOsiander's sign refers to a pulsation that can be felt at the edge of the cervix.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 356.","responses":[{"text":"Jacquemier's sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hegar's sign","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodell's sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ballottement sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osiander's sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13748,"text":"What is the most reliable and only sign of recent delivery in the living?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Forensic Medicine, Topic: Pregnancy and Delivery, Sub-topic: Signs of Recent Delivery in Alive Women.","responses":[{"text":"External os is transverse, irregular and fissured","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lochia serosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disappearance of Arbor vitae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fundus lying 2.5 cm below umbilicus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Body of the uterus twice the length of cervix","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13751,"text":"What are the grounds under which an abortion is carried out where there is a substantial risk if the baby is born, it will likely suffer from physical and mental abnormality?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 34.","responses":[{"text":"Eugenic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Humanitarian","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Socail","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13753,"text":"What is the Glaister-keen rod used for?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 377.","responses":[{"text":"Inserted in vagina for masturbation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To see defensibility of vagina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To determine hymen rupturing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To see the presence or absence of vaginal discharge","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To induce abortion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13754,"text":"A case of alleged rape has been brought to you. On examining the female victim, you determined that the hymen was fimbriated and not ruptured. Therefore, you concluded that the allegations were false. How do you differentiate between a fimbriated and a ruptured hymen?","explanation":"A **fimbriated hymen** is characterized by fringes or finger-like extensions around the vaginal opening. It is a normal anatomical variant. The **mucous membrane** over the notches or fringes is typically intact in a fimbriated hymen. The edges of a fimbriated hymen are usually regular and do not indicate trauma.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Forensic Medicine, Topic: Personality, Sub-topic: Differentiate Between Fimbriated and Ruptured Hymen.","responses":[{"text":"Ruptured hymen can occur naturally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shape of notches is assymetrical in a fimbriated hymen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shape of notches is bilaterally symetrical in a ruptured hymen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ruptured hymen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucous membrane is intact over notches in a fimbriated hymen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13755,"text":"You examine a 40-year-old multiparous female and find hymen remnants in the form of marginal attachments that are thick and irregular. What are these attachments known as?","explanation":"**Carunculae myrtiformes** are small, irregular, tag-like projections at the margin of the vaginal opening. They are remnants of the hymen and are typically seen in women who have had vaginal deliveries.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRuptured hymen refers to the state of the hymen after it has been torn, which can occur due to various reasons including sexual activity and childbirth. However, the specific description of thick and irregular marginal attachments aligns more precisely with carunculae myrtiformes.\r\n\r\nA fimbriated hymen is a type of hymen characterized by fringes or finger-like projections. It is a normal anatomical variation and doesn't specifically refer to postpartum hymenal remnants.\r\n\r\nThe term carunculae hymenales is less commonly used and is not as specific as carunculae myrtiformes in describing the remnants of the hymen following childbirth.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Forensic Medicine, Topic: Personality, Sub-topic: Changes in Hymen After Rupture.","responses":[{"text":"Carunculae hymenales","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triangular projections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fimbriated hymen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ruptured hymen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carunculae myrtiformes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13756,"text":"In the case of sodomy, who is the passive agent?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 388-389.","responses":[{"text":"Rapist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Witness of the act","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Performer of the act","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hearsayer of the act","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"On whom it is performed","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13757,"text":"You are asked to examine a habitual sodomite. Which of the following findings are you most likely going to find in such a case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Confusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruising","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal tear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal fissures","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13758,"text":"A 22-year-old female presented with a complaint of blood in her urine. What is the initial investigation recommended for this patient?","explanation":"**Hematuria** is a concerning symptom that requires evaluation to determine its cause. An initial step in the evaluation of hematuria is to perform an **ultrasound of the kidney, ureters, and bladder** (KUB).\r\n\r\nUltrasound is a non-invasive imaging modality that can provide valuable information about the urinary tract, including the presence of stones, tumors, or structural abnormalities. It is often used as the first-line imaging investigation for patients with hematuria, especially in young individuals.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCT urography is a more comprehensive imaging study that combines CT scanning with contrast to visualize the urinary tract in detail. While it can provide a comprehensive evaluation, it is typically reserved for cases where the ultrasound results are inconclusive or when additional information is needed.\r\n\r\nUrine analysis is an important diagnostic test to confirm the presence of blood in the urine and to assess other urinary parameters. However, it is usually performed in conjunction with imaging.\r\n\r\nUrine culture is performed to identify and diagnose urinary tract infections. It is not the primary investigation for evaluating hematuria but may be performed based on clinical suspicion.\r\n\r\nThe urine dipstick test is a quick and convenient way to detect the presence of blood in the urine. While it can provide an initial indication of hematuria, it does not provide detailed information about the underlying cause, and further evaluation is needed.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1375-1376.","responses":[{"text":"Urine culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine analysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT urography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound kidney, ureters, bladder","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine dipstick test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13759,"text":"A 55-year-old male presented with the complaint of painless hematuria, hypertension, weight loss, pyrexia, and anorexia. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Painless hematuria** is a common symptom of renal cancer and is often one of the first signs. **Hypertension** can be associated with **renal cancer** due to the tumor's effect on kidney function and hormone production.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLower urinary tract infection typically presents with symptoms like burning during urination and increased urinary frequency. Painless hematuria is less common, and systemic symptoms like significant weight loss and pyrexia are not typical.\r\n\r\nWhile adenocarcinoma of the bladder can present with hematuria, other symptoms like hypertension, weight loss, and pyrexia are less typical for bladder cancer.\r\n\r\nPainless hematuria is not a common presenting symptom of prostate cancer.\r\n\r\nAlthough bladder cancer can present with hematuria, hypertension is more suggestive of renal cancer.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1448.","responses":[{"text":"Prostate cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal cancer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower urinary tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urothelial bladder cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma bladder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13760,"text":"A 45-year-old female presented with intermittent flank pain and hematuria. She was recently admitted to a hospital for acute pancreatitis. What is the likely cause of her current condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 947.","responses":[{"text":"Pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower urinary tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperparathyroidism","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13761,"text":"A 60-year-old female came with a history of hematuria, dysuria, and troublesome lower urinary tract symptoms. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 600.","responses":[{"text":"Lower urinary tract infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urothelial bladder cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bladder stones","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13762,"text":"A 22-year-old patient with a history of recent travel to Africa is now complaining of fever, abdominal pain, and blood in the urine. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":"***Schistosoma hematobium*** is a parasitic trematode worm that causes a disease called schistosomiasis. This infection is common in parts of **Africa**, especially in regions with freshwater bodies infested with infected snails, where individuals can get exposed during activities such as swimming or wading in contaminated water. \r\n\r\n*Schistosoma hematobium* primarily affects the urinary tract and can lead to symptoms like **hematuria**, abdominal pain, and fever.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Pseudomonas* is a type of bacteria that can cause various infections, but it is not typically associated with the described symptoms in this context.\r\n\r\n*Aedes aegypti* is a mosquito species responsible for transmitting diseases like dengue, Zika virus, and yellow fever. It is not directly associated with the symptoms described.\r\n\r\n*Plasmodium vivax* is a parasite responsible for causing malaria, which can present with symptoms like fever but is not typically associated with abdominal pain and blood in the urine.\r\n\r\n*Escherichia coli* (E. coli) is a common bacterium that can cause urinary tract infections (UTIs) and may lead to symptoms like fever and hematuria, but it is not specifically associated with travel to Africa.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 338-339.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudomonas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schistosoma hematobium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium vivax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aedes aegypti","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13763,"text":"An 85-year-old male presented with renal cell carcinoma. Which of the following is incorrect?","explanation":"**Radical nephrectomy**, which involves the surgical removal of the entire affected kidney, is a standard treatment for renal cell carcinoma. However, radiotherapy is generally not a primary treatment for localized **renal cell carcinoma**, as these tumors are typically **not responsive to radiation therapy**.\r\n\r\nRadiotherapy may be considered in some cases, such as when the cancer has spread to surrounding tissues or if surgery is not an option due to the patient's overall health. However, it is not routinely given following radical nephrectomy for localized renal cell carcinoma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nUltrasound and triphasic CT urography are the imaging methods of choice for diagnosing renal cell carcinoma and assessing its extent.\r\n\r\nIn 25% of patients, there are no local symptoms initially, and the cancer may be discovered incidentally during imaging for other reasons.\r\n\r\nRenal cell carcinoma occurs more commonly in men than in women.\r\n\r\nA left-sided varicocele may be a presenting feature in a male due to the compression of the left renal vein by the tumor, leading to elevated pressure in the testicular veins and the development of a varicocele. This phenomenon is known as renal vein entrapment syndrome.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 629.","responses":[{"text":"Following radical nephrectomy, radiotherapy should be given","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It occurs more commonly in men","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In 25% of patients there are no local symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A left sided varicocele may be a presenting feature in a male","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound and triphasic CT urography are the imaging methods of choice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13764,"text":"A 70-year-old man who has a history of smoking and complains of hematuria associated with pain in his left groin passes clots that are \"worm-like\". On examination, he has an enlarged left kidney and scrotal swelling. What is the investigation of choice?","explanation":"**Triphasic CT urography** is a comprehensive imaging study used to evaluate the urinary tract, including the kidneys, ureters, and bladder. It allows for the evaluation of the entire urinary tract, identification of any lesions or obstructions, and assessment of blood flow to the kidneys, which can be crucial in cases of hematuria.\r\n\r\nThe patient's symptoms of **hematuria**, the passage of \"worm-like\" clots, and an enlarged left kidney raise concerns about potential urinary tract pathology, such as kidney stones, tumors, or obstructions. **Scrotal swelling** may also be related to the underlying urinary issue, and it's important to assess both the urinary and scrotal regions.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n\r\nUrine detailed report (DR) and culture and sensitivity (CS) are important for assessing the urine for infection and providing information about the composition of the clots or any underlying urinary issues. However, imaging studies are also needed for a more comprehensive evaluation of the anatomy.\r\n\r\nWhile ultrasound can be used to evaluate scrotal swelling, it may not provide the necessary information about the entire urinary tract.\r\n\r\nUltrasound of the abdomen can provide some information about the kidneys and urinary tract, but it may not offer the same level of detail as CT urography.\r\n\r\nCT kidney, ureters, bladder (KUB) is a common imaging study for evaluating urinary tract issues but may not provide the same comprehensive assessment of the entire urinary tract as triphasic CT urography.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Surgery, Topic: Clinical approach and management of haematuria, Sub-topic: Hematuria flowchart.","responses":[{"text":"CT kidney, ureters, bladder (KUB)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triphasic CT urography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound scrotum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine detailed report (DR) and culture and sensitivity (CS)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15773,"text":"Immediately after delivery, the uterine fundus lies at which of the following levels?","explanation":"The position of the uterine fundus immediately after delivery is an important indicator of uterine involution (the process by which the uterus returns to its non-pregnant state). Immediately after delivery, the uterine fundus is typically at a level of 12 cm above the symphysis pubis.","reference":"Kenny LC, Myers JE, eds. Obstetrics by Ten Teachers. 20th ed. CRC Press; 2017: 273.","responses":[{"text":"12 cm above symphysis pubis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Can not be palpated abdominally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At symphysis pubis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At umbilicus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 cm below umbilicus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16022,"text":"Which of the following factors help distinguish that hematuria is of renal origin and not from the bladder?","explanation":"Hematuria, or the presence of blood in the urine, can arise from various regions within the urinary tract, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra. Determining the origin is crucial for appropriate diagnosis and management. Among the options listed, RBC casts are indicative of a renal origin for the hematuria. \r\n\r\nRBC casts form within the tubular lumen of the kidneys when red blood cells aggregate and become enmeshed within a proteinaceous matrix. The presence of RBC casts in the urine signifies glomerular or tubulointerstitial inflammation and is a hallmark of glomerular bleeding. In contrast, conditions affecting the lower urinary tract (e.g., bladder infections or tumors) will produce hematuria but not RBC casts.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 614.","responses":[{"text":"Gross hematuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sterile pyuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"WBC casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RBC casts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobinuria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20692,"text":"Which of the following is the best treatment for euvolemic hyponatremia?","explanation":"**Euvolemic hyponatremia** refers to a situation where a person has low blood sodium levels, but their total body water is within normal limits. This condition can occur in various clinical settings, including the syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) or certain medications.\r\n\r\n**3% hypertonic saline** is the preferred treatment for euvolemic hyponatremia because it provides a concentrated sodium solution to raise blood sodium levels.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWater restriction may be recommended in some cases of euvolemic hyponatremia, especially when the condition is mild. However, for symptomatic hyponatremia, hypertonic saline is more effective.\r\n\r\nDextrose saline is not typically used as the primary treatment for euvolemic hyponatremia.\r\n\r\nDextrose water is not an appropriate treatment for euvolemic hyponatremia because it does not provide sodium to correct the low blood sodium levels.\r\n\r\nNormal saline (0.9% saline) is isotonic and is typically used for fluid resuscitation and replacement in cases of dehydration or hypovolemia.","reference":"Sahay M, Sahay R. Hyponatremia: A practical approach. Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism. Published 2014. Accessed October 27, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4192979/","responses":[{"text":"Dextrose saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Water restriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.9% saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3% hypertonic saline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dextrose water","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20743,"text":"A 50-year-old female patient comes to the outpatient department with frothy urine, edema, and low urine output. She has been a known case of diabetes and hypertension for almost 20 years. Her laboratory reports show increased creatinine levels and is diagnosed with diabetic nephropathy. What is the histological appearance of diabetic nephropathy?","explanation":"**Diabetic nephropathy** is a common complication of long-standing diabetes mellitus, especially in patients with poorly controlled blood sugar levels. It is characterized by structural and functional changes in the kidneys, particularly affecting the glomeruli. The key histological feature of diabetic nephropathy is **glomerulosclerosis**, which refers to the scarring or fibrosis of the glomeruli.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTram track or double contouring is characteristic of membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis, not diabetic nephropathy.\r\n\r\nSpike and dome appearance is typically seen in membranous nephropathy.\r\n\r\nSub-epithelial dense deposits are more associated with post-infectious glomerulonephritis or membranous nephropathy.\r\n\r\nCrescentic glomerulonephritis is a separate entity characterized by the presence of crescents in the glomeruli and is not a typical feature of diabetic nephropathy.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 1111.","responses":[{"text":"Glomerulosclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spike and dome appearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sub-epithelial dense deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tram tract or double contouring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescent glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20890,"text":"A person taking a diuretic for a heart issue is prescribed gentamicin. He later complained of dizziness and tinnitus. Which of the following drugs is responsible for these symptoms?","explanation":"**Ethacrynic acid** is a loop diuretic commonly used to treat conditions like heart failure and edema by promoting diuresis. However, it is known to have a higher risk of causing **ototoxicity**, which can manifest as symptoms like dizziness and tinnitus.\r\n\r\nOtotoxicity refers to damage to the structures of the inner ear, including the cochlea, which can lead to auditory and vestibular symptoms.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAcetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor and a diuretic that is more commonly associated with metabolic and electrolyte disturbances, such as metabolic acidosis and potassium imbalances, rather than dizziness and tinnitus.\r\n\r\nSpironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic, and its main side effect is hyperkalemia (elevated potassium levels).\r\n\r\nMannitol is an osmotic diuretic used to reduce intracranial pressure or promote diuresis in certain medical situations. While it can have side effects, they are not typically related to dizziness and tinnitus.\r\n\r\nHydrochlorothiazide is a thiazide diuretic commonly used for treating hypertension and edema. It is not typically associated with dizziness and tinnitus to the extent that loop diuretics like ethacrynic acid can be.","reference":"Aribo, Chade, and Daniel K. Ng. “Ethacrynic Acid.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2023. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558988/","responses":[{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mannitol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethacrynic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocholorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20910,"text":"Many diuretics are known to cause hypokalemia. Which one of the following drugs causes hyperkalemia?","explanation":"Spironolactone is a **potassium-sparing diuretic**. It works by blocking the action of aldosterone, a hormone that promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the kidneys. By inhibiting aldosterone, **spironolactone** leads to increased retention of potassium in the body, potentially causing hyperkalemia (high potassium levels in the blood.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBumetanide, torsemide, and furosemide are loop diuretics. Loop diuretics are known for their strong diuretic effect, which can lead to potassium loss (hypokalemia) as a side effect.\r\n\r\nHydrochlorothiazide is a thiazide diuretic. Thiazide diuretics also promote potassium loss and can lead to hypokalemia in some individuals.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 465.","responses":[{"text":"Hydrochlorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Torsemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bumetanide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20911,"text":"A 70-year-old man is planning to undergo transurethral resection of his prostate. Which of the following complications can arise after the surgery?","explanation":"**Transurethral resection of the prostate** (TURP) involves the removal of prostate tissue that may obstruct the urethra. In some cases, this procedure can lead to the disruption of the internal sphincter at the bladder neck, which can result in **retrograde ejaculation**.\r\n\r\nRetrograde ejaculation occurs when semen is directed into the bladder instead of being expelled through the urethra during ejaculation. While it does not typically pose a significant health risk, it can result in infertility because sperm are not ejaculated in the usual manner.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile postoperative urinary retention can occur after TURP due to swelling or irritation of the urethra, it is not a complication directly associated with the procedure itself.\r\n\r\nThe success of TURP depends on various factors, but it is not typically described as a complication. Complications can arise from the surgery, but failure itself is not a common complication.\r\n\r\nDizziness may occur postoperatively, but it is not a direct complication of TURP. It may be associated with factors such as anesthesia, medication, or other postoperative issues.\r\n\r\nRenal failure is not a typical complication of TURP. However, in rare cases, severe complications or infections post-surgery could potentially impact renal function.","reference":"O’Connell, P. Ronan, et al., editors. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed., CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group, 2023: 1466.","responses":[{"text":"Retrograde ejaculation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Surgery failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post operational urinary retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal Failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dizziness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20912,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient with a known case of diabetes presented to the outpatient department. His laboratory investigations showed hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, and hyperkalemia. Which of the following can be the cause of these metabolic abnormalities?","explanation":"**Chronic kidney disease** (CKD) can lead to disturbances in electrolyte and mineral metabolism. As kidney function declines, the kidneys become less efficient at filtering waste and maintaining proper balances of minerals and electrolytes.\r\n\r\n**Hypocalcemia** occurs partly due to decreased vitamin D activation, leading to reduced calcium absorption. **Hyperphosphatemia** is a result of decreased phosphate excretion. **Hyperkalemia** arises from the reduced excretion of potassium. These findings are common in advanced stages of CKD.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPhenylketonuria is a genetic disorder affecting the metabolism of phenylalanine, leading to its accumulation. It does not typically present with the electrolyte disturbances mentioned.\r\n\r\nHomocystinuria is another genetic metabolic disorder affecting the metabolism of methionine. Like phenylketonuria, it doesn't cause the described electrolyte and mineral imbalances.\r\n\r\nWhile acute kidney injuries can lead to similar electrolyte disturbances, the chronicity of the patient's condition (indicated by his longstanding diabetes) points more towards CKD.\r\n\r\nPrimary hyperthyroidism affects thyroid hormone levels and can lead to hypercalcemia, not hypocalcemia. It also does not typically cause hyperphosphatemia or hyperkalemia.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 363, 369.","responses":[{"text":"Homocystinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic kidney disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylketonuria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20916,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient with a known case of diabetes presented to the outpatient department. His laboratory investigations showed hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, and hyperkalemia. He was diagnosed with chronic kidney failure and now complained of shortness of breath, lack of energy, and pale skin. What could be the cause of his anemia?","explanation":"The kidneys produce **erythropoietin**, a hormone that stimulates the bone marrow to produce red blood cells. In chronic kidney failure, the kidney's ability to produce adequate erythropoietin is compromised, leading to a decrease in red blood cell production, which causes anemia. This type of anemia is specifically associated with **chronic kidney disease**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThalassemia is a genetic disorder affecting hemoglobin synthesis. It would typically present earlier in life and is less likely to be the cause of anemia in this scenario, especially in the absence of a family history or prior diagnosis.\r\n\r\nWhile chronic diseases can cause anemia due to chronic inflammation, in this context, the more direct cause related to kidney failure is erythropoietin deficiency. Anemia of chronic disease is typically normocytic, whereas anemia due to erythropoietin deficiency can often present as normocytic or mild microcytic anemia.\r\n\r\nAcute renal injury could cause anemia, but the patient's presentation is more consistent with chronic kidney failure.\r\n\r\nWhile iron deficiency anemia is a common type of anemia, the patient's clinical picture and lab findings are more indicative of erythropoietin deficiency associated with chronic kidney failure.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 386.","responses":[{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythropoietin deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute renal injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20917,"text":"Which investigation will be done on a woman with a complaint of urinary incontinence?","explanation":"**Urodynamic testing** is a specialized set of tests that assess how well the bladder, urethra, and associated muscles function. It helps diagnose the underlying causes of urinary incontinence and provides valuable information on bladder function, pressure, and urine flow. It is considered the **gold standard** for diagnosing **urinary incontinence** and can help determine the type of incontinence.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile ultrasound KUB may be useful for visualizing the urinary tract and identifying some abnormalities, it is not typically the initial investigation for evaluating urinary incontinence.\r\n\r\nCT scans are not routinely used as the first-line investigation for urinary incontinence, unless other underlying conditions or structural abnormalities are suspected.\r\n\r\nUltrasound bladder with pre and post void volumes: This ultrasound examination can help measure bladder capacity and assess for post-void residual urine volume, which can be useful in some cases of urinary incontinence but is not the primary diagnostic test for the condition.\r\n\r\nMicturating cystoureterogram (MCU) is a contrast study that involves imaging the bladder and urethra during voiding. It is typically used to evaluate structural abnormalities or vesicoureteral reflux in individuals, especially in children, with recurrent urinary tract infections. It is not a routine investigation for urinary incontinence in women.","reference":"O’Connell, P. Ronan, et al., editors. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed., CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group, 2023: 1429.","responses":[{"text":"Ultrasound KUB","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound bladder with pre and post void volumes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urodynamic testing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Micturating cystoureterogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21010,"text":"A student was taking a history in a surgery ward when a patient said that he had donated his kidney two years ago. Which of the following is the most common reason for someone to donate a kidney to an unknown person?","explanation":"In some regions or countries, there are programs or systems that allow for compensated **kidney donation**. These programs may provide **financial incentives** or compensation to individuals who choose to donate a kidney to a recipient in need. The aim is to increase the pool of available kidneys for transplantation and reduce the shortage of organs.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nKidney donation to unknown persons is not a tradition in most cultures.\r\n\r\nKidney donation for social or ritualistic reasons is not a common practice and may not be associated with rising to a higher social level.\r\n\r\nWhile some religions emphasize the importance of organ donation for the greater good, donating a kidney to an unknown person is not typically a religious obligation.\r\n\r\nDonating a kidney to get rid of it is not a common or valid reason for kidney donation. Kidney donation is usually motivated by a desire to save or improve the life of another person through transplantation.","reference":"Inthorn, Julia, et al. “Impact of Gender and Professional Education on Attitudes towards Financial Incentives for Organ Donation: Results of a Survey among 755 Students of Medicine and Economics in Germany.” BMC Medical Ethics, 5 July 2014, https://doi.org/10.1186/1472-6939-15-56.","responses":[{"text":"To get rid of one kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Financial incentive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a tradition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a ritual to rise to higher level in society","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an obligation according to one's religions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21011,"text":"While operating on a man after road traffic accident, doctor found scarring on a kidney. Scarring of the kidney along with dilation in a completely asymptomatic patient can be found in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"**Chronic pyelonephritis** is a long-term inflammatory condition of the kidney. It often results from recurrent or persistent kidney infections and can lead to **scarring** (fibrosis) of the renal tissue. Over time, this scarring can cause dilation of the renal pelvis and calyces, leading to a condition known as **hydronephrosis**.\r\n\r\nHydronephrosis refers to the enlargement or dilation of the renal pelvis and calyces due to the obstruction of urine flow within the kidney. It can be asymptomatic in some cases, especially in the early stages when kidney function is relatively preserved.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTrauma-related kidney injuries can lead to scarring and dilation, but they are typically associated with a history of trauma and may not be asymptomatic.\r\n\r\nAcute pyelonephritis is an acute bacterial infection of the kidney and is typically associated with symptoms such as fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms.\r\n\r\nHematuria (blood in the urine) is a symptom rather than a condition. It can be associated with various kidney conditions, but it does not directly explain the presence of scarring and dilation.\r\n\r\nAcute tubular injury, often seen in conditions like acute kidney injury (AKI), is not typically associated with chronic scarring and dilation of the kidney.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 430.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic pyelonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney injury due to trauma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21012,"text":"A 27-year-old man who lived alone in a studio died suddenly. Upon post-mortem examination, several raised yellow abscesses on the kidney surface were seen. Which of the following diseases is associated with rapid loss of renal function over days to weeks?","explanation":"**Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis** (RPGN) is a condition characterized by a rapid decline in kidney function over a relatively short period, typically days to weeks. It is associated with inflammation and damage to the glomeruli.\r\n\r\nRaised **yellow abscesses** on the kidney surface can be a characteristic finding in RPGN, often indicating severe glomerular involvement and tissue destruction.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAcute interstitial nephritis involves inflammation of the renal interstitium and tubules, but it typically does not present with raised yellow abscesses on the kidney surface.\r\n\r\nChronic pyelonephritis is a long-term inflammatory condition of the kidney that develops over a prolonged period. It is not associated with rapid loss of renal function.\r\n\r\nNephrotic syndrome is characterized by heavy proteinuria, edema, and hypoalbuminemia. It does not typically cause rapid loss of renal function as described.\r\n\r\nAcute pyelonephritis is an infection of the kidney and can lead to symptoms like fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms, but it may not result in rapid loss of renal function over days to weeks.\r\n\r\nAcute tubular injury, often seen in conditions like acute kidney injury (AKI), can result in a decline in renal function, but it may not present with raised yellow abscesses on the kidney surface.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 401.","responses":[{"text":"Acute interstitial nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21013,"text":"A 23-year-old female presents to the outpatient clinic with complaints of increased frequency, urgency, and dysuria for the past 2 weeks. Her history is also significant for suprapubic discomfort and her laboratory reports show increased nitrites and leukocyte count. What is the single most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Cystitis** is an inflammation of the urinary bladder, commonly caused by a bacterial urinary tract infection (UTI). The symptoms described by the patient, including increased frequency, urgency, **dysuria**, and suprapubic discomfort, are typical of cystitis. Additionally, the presence of increased **nitrites** and **leukocytes** in the laboratory reports suggest a urinary tract infection. Cystitis is more common in females, and the presentation matches the clinical features of a lower urinary tract infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nUrethral strictures involve the narrowing of the urethra and typically result in difficulties with urine flow and emptying, which may present with different symptoms.\r\n\r\nUrethritis is inflammation of the urethra and may cause symptoms similar to cystitis but is less likely to cause suprapubic discomfort.\r\n\r\nPyelonephritis is an infection of the kidneys and typically presents with symptoms such as fever, flank pain, and systemic symptoms in addition to urinary symptoms.\r\n\r\nBladder stones may cause urinary symptoms, but they are less common in young females and would not typically result in increased nitrites and leukocytes in the urine.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1441.","responses":[{"text":"Urethral stricture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bladder stones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urethritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21049,"text":"Which of the following defects is found in autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease on a molecular level?","explanation":"**Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease** (ADPKD) is a genetic disorder characterized by the development of fluid-filled cysts in the kidneys. The underlying genetic mutations associated with ADPKD are primarily found in two genes, PKD1 and PKD2. These mutations disrupt the function of primary **cilia** and **centrosomes** in renal epithelial cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMitochondria are not the primary focus of molecular defects in this condition.\r\n\r\nThe endoplasmic reticulum is not the primary focus of molecular defects in this condition.\r\n\r\nA brush border defect is not a characteristic molecular defect associated with ADPKD.\r\n\r\nPodocytes are specialized cells in the kidney that are primarily associated with glomerular function and filtration. Molecular defects in ADPKD primarily involve cilia and centrosomes in renal epithelial cells rather than podocytes.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 942.","responses":[{"text":"Cilia and endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cilia and centrosome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cilia and mitochondria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Podocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brush border defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21050,"text":"Both adult and childhood polycystic kidney disease cause end-stage renal disease. What is correct regarding autosomal recessive cystic kidney disease?","explanation":"**Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease** (ARPKD) is a genetic disorder characterized by the development of cysts in the kidneys, leading to kidney enlargement and often causing severe kidney-related problems in infants and **children**. It is typically diagnosed during the neonatal or early childhood period.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAutosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) is the more common form of polycystic kidney disease in adults. It tends to manifest later in life, often during adulthood and is characterized by the development of kidney cysts that gradually enlarge over time.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 943.","responses":[{"text":"Mostly occur in old age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mostly occur in children","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mostly occur in both adults and children","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mostly occur in adults","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mostly occur in intrauterine period","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21051,"text":"Which of the following can be used as the appropriate statistical test to study the IQ levels of 25 students (sample size is less than 30)?","explanation":"The **t-test** is used to compare the means of two groups to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between them, most likely the IQ levels of one group (the 25 students) to a known or expected value in this case.\r\n\r\nThe t-test is suitable for small sample sizes and is commonly used when comparing means, especially when determining if the difference between the means is statistically significant.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAnalysis of variance (ANOVA) is typically used when comparing means across more than two groups.\r\n\r\nChi-square is used for categorical data analysis, such as examining the association between two categorical variables.\r\n\r\nRegression is used to analyze relationships between variables and make predictions based on those relationships.\r\n\r\nMann-Whitney U test is a non-parametric test used to compare two independent groups when the data is not normally distributed, but the T-test is more appropriate when dealing with IQ scores, which are often approximately normally distributed.","reference":"Lani, James. “T-Test.” Statistics Solutions, 12 Nov. 2009, https://www.statisticssolutions.com/t-test/.","responses":[{"text":"Anova","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Regression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mann-Whitney U test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chi square","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21052,"text":"A 70-year-old male is having urinary incontinence and nocturia. He also complains of dribbling of urine and hematuria. Which investigation should be done to rule out bladder outlet obstruction?","explanation":"**Urodynamic tests** assess how well the bladder, sphincters, and urethra are storing and releasing urine. They are particularly useful in evaluating the functional aspects of **bladder outlet obstruction**. These tests can help determine whether the symptoms are due to a blockage (such as from an enlarged prostate) or a problem with the bladder's function.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile cystoscopy can help visualize structural abnormalities or pathologies within the bladder and urethra, it may not be the first-line investigation specifically for bladder outlet obstruction.\r\n\r\nDigital rectal examination (DRE) is useful in assessing the prostate, which can contribute to bladder outlet obstruction, especially in older men. However, it provides limited information compared to urodynamic studies and is more of a preliminary examination.\r\n\r\nEndoscopy refers to procedures that look inside the body and can include cystoscopy. Like cystoscopy, it's more for direct visualization rather than functional assessment.\r\n\r\nProstate-specific antigen (PSA) testing is used primarily as a screening tool for prostate cancer. While an enlarged prostate can lead to bladder outlet obstruction, PSA alone cannot diagnose the cause of urinary symptoms.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 437.","responses":[{"text":"Urodynamic investigations","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digital rectal examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate specific antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21053,"text":"A person who is diabetic for many years develops anemia, hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, fatigue, and body aches. His previous medical history reveals that he has been diagnosed with osteoporosis along with chronic renal failure for which he has been on dialysis for the past 4 months. Which of the following correctly describes his condition?","explanation":"**Renal osteodystrophy** is a term used to describe the bone pathology associated with chronic kidney disease (CKD). It encompasses a spectrum of bone disorders due to the alterations in mineral metabolism and bone turnover caused by renal failure. \r\n\r\nAs kidney function declines, the ability to excrete phosphate decreases, leading to **increased phosphate levels** in the blood. Meanwhile, reduced renal synthesis of active vitamin D leads to decreased calcium absorption from the gut, resulting in **hypocalcemia**. The low calcium levels stimulate parathyroid hormone (PTH) secretion, which tries to maintain calcium levels by increasing bone resorption, eventually leading to bone demineralization and **osteoporosis**.\r\n\r\n**Anemia** and fatigue are commonly associated with CKD due to reduced erythropoietin production by the kidneys.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPrimary hyperparathyroidism is characterized by hypercalcemia due to inappropriate secretion of PTH from the parathyroid glands, which is not the case here.\r\n\r\nWhile the patient does have CKD, this term does not specifically describe the bone and mineral metabolism disorders seen in the patient.\r\n\r\nSecondary hyperparathyroidism is a component of renal osteodystrophy in the context of CKD, but it does not encompass the entire clinical picture, including bone changes.\r\n\r\nTertiary hyperparathyroidism refers to a state where the parathyroid glands become autonomously hyperactive, typically after long-standing secondary hyperparathyroidism. It usually presents with hypercalcemia, which is not indicated in this scenario.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 1181.","responses":[{"text":"Secondary hyperparathyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary hyperparathyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary hyperparathyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal osteodystrophy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21054,"text":"A patient presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of severe pain in the loin region along with oliguria, hematuria, and burning micturition. Which of the following investigations is considered a gold standard for detecting a kidney stone?","explanation":"Computed tomography of the kidneys, ureters, and bladder (**CT-KUB**) is considered the **gold standard** for diagnosing **kidney stones**. It is highly sensitive and can accurately detect the presence, size, location, and composition of kidney stones. It is particularly useful when prompt and accurate diagnosis is needed due to severe symptoms, as described in the patient's presentation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMRI can provide detailed images of the kidneys, but it is not the primary imaging modality used for diagnosing kidney stones. CT scans are more commonly employed for this purpose due to their high sensitivity and specificity.\r\n\r\nPyelograms involve the use of contrast agents and X-rays to visualize the urinary tract. While they can help identify obstructions or anatomical abnormalities, they are less commonly used than CT scans for detecting kidney stones.\r\n\r\nCystoscopy is a procedure used to visualize the inside of the bladder and urethra and is not the primary method for detecting kidney stones within the renal system.\r\n\r\nWhile plain X-rays can detect some kidney stones, they are not as sensitive as CT scans in visualizing smaller stones or stones that are not radiopaque.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 432","responses":[{"text":"Cystoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plain X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyelogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT-KUB","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21067,"text":"A patient presented to the clinic with the symptoms of the nephrotic syndrome. Upon investigation, his glomeruli were found to be thick, and hypercellular with a double contouring of the glomerular basement membrane. There were thick subendothelial electron-dense deposits clearly visible. His serum levels showed hypocomplementemia, especially low levels of C3. Which of the following is the most appropriate diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis** (MPGN), is characterized by the thickening and hypercellularity of the glomeruli with **double contouring** of the glomerular **basement membrane**. Clinical features of MPGN include proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, edema, and hyperlipidemia, which are associated with nephrotic syndrome.\r\n\r\nIn type I MPGN, immune complexes are deposited in the subendothelial space, leading to complement activation and subsequent hypocomplementemia, particularly **low C3** levels.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDouble contouring, subendothelial deposits, and hypocomplementemia are more indicative of MPGN rather than steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome.\r\n\r\nIgA nephropathy typically presents with IgA deposits in the mesangium.\r\n\r\nFocal glomerulosclerosis is characterized by scarring (sclerosis) in some, but not all, glomeruli.\r\n\r\nMinimal change disease is characterized by minimal or no changes in the glomeruli under light microscopy.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 918.","responses":[{"text":"Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroid resistant nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimal change disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21068,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents with flank pain and urinary symptoms. A diagnosis of solitary cysts was made. A single cyst is diagnostically important for what reason?","explanation":"**Solitary cysts** in the kidney are relatively common and are usually benign. However, their presence on imaging studies, such as ultrasound or CT scans, can sometimes **mimic** the appearance of **renal cell carcinoma**. Therefore, it is essential to differentiate between benign cysts and potentially cancerous tumors to guide further management.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe development of solitary cysts is not typically associated with early childhood but can occur later in life.\r\n\r\nSolitary cysts are generally not associated with renal failure in their early stages. They are more commonly benign and asymptomatic.\r\n\r\nSolitary cysts themselves are not considered life-threatening.\r\n\r\nThe prevalence of solitary cysts in the kidney is not significantly biased toward one gender and can occur in both males and females.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 950.","responses":[{"text":"Is more common in males","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leads to renal failure in early stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appears in early childhood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has to be differentiated with the renal carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Is a life threatening condition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21107,"text":"Which of the following is the best method for waste disposal as it produces the least amount of pollution?","explanation":null,"reference":"Waste Incineration - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemistry/waste-incineration#:~:text=An%20alternative%20method%20of%20waste,ash%20(Waite%2C%201995). Accessed 20 Nov. 2023","responses":[{"text":"Dewatering","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incineration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thermal treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoclave","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Landfill","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21108,"text":"A 40-year-old man comes to the clinic with a complaint of bleeding and pain during and after urination. He was treated for a urinary tract infection several times in the past. Which of the following can be the cause of this condition if the pain is radiating to the wards of the perineum?","explanation":"**Bladder stones** can irritate the bladder wall, leading to dysuria and hematuria. The pain can radiate to the perineal area between the anus and the scrotum or vulva. Additionally, the history of recurrent urinary tract infections (UTIs) could be related, as bladder stones can be both a cause and a consequence of UTIs due to their tendency to harbor bacteria and disrupt urine flow.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile a stone in the ureter can cause significant pain, this pain typically radiates to the back, side, or groin, not primarily to the perineum. Hematuria can occur, but the primary symptom is usually colicky pain rather than dysuria.\r\n\r\nBenign prostate hypertrophy (BPH) can cause urinary symptoms due to obstruction of the urinary tract. However, it is less likely to cause bleeding and severe pain, especially pain radiating to the perineum.\r\n\r\nRecurrent UTIs can cause dysuria and hematuria, but they are less likely to cause radiating perineal pain unless there is a complication such as a bladder stone.\r\n\r\nLike ureteric stones, renal stones usually cause pain that radiates to the back, side, or groin. Hematuria can occur, but the pain characteristic of renal stones is colicky.","reference":"“Bladder Stones.” Nhs.Uk, 8 June 2018, https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/bladder-stones/","responses":[{"text":"Bladder stone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal stone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign prostate hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ureteric stone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent urinary tract infections","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21123,"text":"A 30-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with complaints of urinary incontinence, fever, and painful micturition. She also complained that she sometimes sees the pus coming out along with the urine. What will be the first investigation that can be done in this case?","explanation":"Urinary incontinence, fever, painful micturition, and the complaint of pus coming out with the urine is highly suggestive of a **urinary tract infection** (UTI). To confirm the diagnosis and identify the causative organism, a urinalysis and urine culture should be performed.\r\n\r\n**Urinalysis** can provide information about the presence of white blood cells (indicating inflammation or infection), red blood cells, and other abnormal elements in the urine.\r\n\r\n**Urine culture** is essential to identify the type of bacteria causing the infection and to determine its sensitivity to antibiotics. This information is crucial for selecting the appropriate antibiotic therapy.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCystoscopy is an invasive procedure that involves inserting a scope into the bladder and is typically not the first investigation for a suspected UTI. It may be considered if there are recurrent UTIs or other underlying urinary tract issues.\r\n\r\nMid-stream urine culture and microscopy is an appropriate investigation but microscopy is only one aspect of urinalysis and would not be preferred instead of a more detailed report.\r\n\r\nWhile ultrasound may have a role in evaluating urinary tract anatomy and looking for structural abnormalities, it is not the first step in diagnosing a UTI.\r\n\r\nA prostate examination is not relevant to females.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 437.","responses":[{"text":"Prostate examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mid stream urine culture and microscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinalysis and culture","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21124,"text":"Which of the following correctly defines Montgomery tubercles?","explanation":"**Montgomery tubercles**, also known as Montgomery glands or areolar glands, are small, raised bumps or glands on the **areola**. These glands contain **sebaceous and sweat glands**.\r\n\r\nDuring pregnancy and lactation, these glands can become more prominent and secrete oils that help lubricate and protect the nipple and areola, as well as provide moisture for the breastfeeding baby.","reference":"“Montgomery’s Tubercles: Definition, in Pregnancy, Purpose, and More.” Healthline, 5 Dec. 2017, https://www.healthline.com/health/montgomerys-tubercles.","responses":[{"text":"Pigmentation around breast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged sebaceous glands around nipples","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pigmented raised line from pubis to umbilicus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pigmented lines on the chest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluid discharge from breast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21125,"text":"Which of the following can be used as a first-line agent in the treatment of bladder carcinoma in situ?","explanation":"**Intravesical Bacillus Calmette-Guérin** (BCG) immunotherapy is considered the first-line treatment for bladder carcinoma in situ. BCG is a weakened form of the tuberculosis bacterium that is used to stimulate the immune system and target cancer cells in the bladder lining. It is highly effective in treating bladder carcinoma in situ and reducing the risk of disease recurrence and progression.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTransurethral resection of bladder tumor (TURBT) is commonly performed for diagnostic purposes and may be used in conjunction with intravesical therapies, but it is not a first-line treatment for CIS.\r\n\r\nCombined chemotherapy may be used in some cases but is typically reserved for more advanced or invasive bladder cancer.\r\n\r\nCystectomy (removal of the bladder) is considered in cases of high-risk CIS that do not respond to other treatments or when there is progression to invasive cancer.\r\n\r\nIntravesical mitomycin C is another intravesical chemotherapy option but is often considered a second-line treatment when BCG is not effective or not tolerated.","reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Cystectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravesical BCG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trans urethral resection of bladder tumor.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Combined chemotherapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravesical mitomycin C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21126,"text":"Which of the following would have decreased serum levels in immune complex-mediated injury to the kidney?","explanation":"**Immune complex-mediated injury** to the kidney involves the deposition of immune complexes in the glomeruli and the activation of the complement system. These immune complexes can cause inflammation and damage to the renal tissue.\r\n\r\n**Complement proteins** are crucial components of the innate immune system and are involved in the inflammatory response. In immune complex-mediated kidney injury, the complement system is activated and consumed locally at the site of inflammation within the kidney. This leads to a **decrease** in the levels of circulating complement proteins in the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCreatinine is a waste product of muscle metabolism and is used as a marker of renal function. In kidney injury, especially when the glomerular filtration rate (GFR) decreases, serum creatinine levels typically rise, indicating impaired kidney function.\r\n\r\nAlbumin is a protein synthesized by the liver and plays a critical role in maintaining oncotic pressure in the blood vessels. In kidney injury, especially in conditions like nephrotic syndrome, there can be increased urinary loss of albumin, leading to hypoalbuminemia.\r\n\r\nHagman factor (factor XII) is involved in the intrinsic pathway of blood coagulation and has no direct relationship with immune complex-mediated kidney injury.\r\n\r\nHemoglobin is a protein found in red blood cells and is responsible for carrying oxygen. In the context of kidney injury, hemoglobin levels may not necessarily be affected unless there is concurrent hemolysis or bleeding.","reference":"Poppelaars, Felix, and Joshua M. Thurman. “Complement-Mediated Kidney Diseases.” Molecular Immunology, 1 Dec. 2020, https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0161589020305204.","responses":[{"text":"Creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hagman factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complement proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21127,"text":"A 20-year-old female patient presented to the outpatient department with complaints of hematuria and edema. She had a history of sore throat around 14 days back. Upon investigation, it was found that her urine contained red blood cell casts and mild proteinuria while microscopy showed crescentic proliferation of glomerular epithelial cells and segmental glomerular necrosis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis** (RPGN) is characterized by a rapidly deteriorating renal function often associated with hematuria, proteinuria, and red blood cell casts in the urine. It frequently follows an upper respiratory tract infection, which is evident from the patient's history of a sore throat. The crescentic proliferation of glomerular epithelial cells and glomerular necrosis seen in microscopy are typical findings in RPGN, making it the most likely diagnosis in this case.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS typically presents with microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury.\r\n\r\nPost-infectious glomerulonephritis (PIGN) usually occurs 1-4 weeks after a streptococcal infection. While there is a history of a sore throat, the presentation with crescentic proliferation and segmental glomerular necrosis is more indicative of RPGN.\r\n\r\nFocal glomerulosclerosis typically presents with proteinuria and nephrotic syndrome, which are not the predominant features in this case.\r\n\r\nDiabetic nephropathy is associated with diabetes mellitus and typically presents with proteinuria, hypertension, and other diabetes-related symptoms. It is not consistent with the clinical findings in this patient.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 910.","responses":[{"text":"Focal glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic uremic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Post infectious glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21128,"text":"A 12-year-old boy presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of hematuria and proteinuria. He has a history of a skin infection that presented with blisters. Upon investigation by immunofluorescence microscopy, there were granular deposits of IgG and C3, and sometimes IgM in the mesangium along the glomerular basement membrane. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis** (PSGN) is an immune-mediated renal disease that typically occurs after an infection with certain strains of group A streptococcus bacteria. It often presents with hematuria, proteinuria, and other renal symptoms.\r\n\r\nImmunofluorescence microscopy shows granular deposits of IgG, C3, and sometimes IgM in the mesangium along the glomerular basement membrane. This pattern of immunofluorescence is typical of PSGN and reflects immune complex deposition in the glomeruli.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile other forms of glomerulonephritis, such as membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis and lupus nephritis, can also present with hematuria and proteinuria, the combination of a preceding streptococcal infection and the specific immunofluorescence findings strongly suggest PSGN in this case.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 909.","responses":[{"text":"Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal segmental glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lupus nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post streptococcal glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21129,"text":"Which of the following is not present in oral rehydration therapy?","explanation":"**Oral rehydration therapy** (ORT) is a method used to treat dehydration, especially in cases of diarrhea or vomiting, by replacing lost fluids and electrolytes. The essential components of ORT typically are listed below.\r\n\r\n**Sodium chloride** to replace lost sodium ions (salt) due to dehydration.\r\n\r\n**Potassium chloride** to replace lost potassium ions.\r\n\r\n**Trisodium citrate** helps maintain the body's acid-base balance and enhances the absorption of sodium and water in the intestines.\r\n\r\n**Glucose** provides a source of energy and enhances the absorption of sodium and water in the intestines.","reference":"“ORT and ORS: What Is the Difference?” Glimpse (Dhaka, Bangladesh), vol. 16, no. 2–3, June 1994. pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov, https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12345472/.","responses":[{"text":"Potassium chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium carbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trisodium citrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21130,"text":"A 29-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of hematuria and frothy urine. She also gives a history of joint pain in small fingers, knees, and hip but there is no deformity upon examination in any of these joints. She sometimes feels irritated by bright lights. What is the probable diagnosis of this condition?","explanation":"**Systemic lupus erythematosus** (SLE) is an autoimmune disease that can affect various organs and systems, including the kidneys. The patient's presentation with hematuria and frothy urine suggests possible renal involvement, which can occur in SLE as a condition called lupus nephritis. Joint involvement in SLE can cause arthralgia without obvious joint deformities.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile diabetes leading to nephropathy, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, hypertension-mediated nephropathy, and cryoglobulinemia can also present with renal manifestations, the combination of arthralgia, photosensitivity, and urinary symptoms strongly points toward systemic lupus erythematosus as the probable diagnosis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 228.","responses":[{"text":"Rapidly progressive golerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes leading to nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryoglobinemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension mediated nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21131,"text":"A 30-year-old female patient presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of hematuria. She had a history of alopecia, photosensitivity, and oral ulcers. She seemed very conscious about a butterfly-shaped rash on her cheeks. Upon investigation, she had a proteinuria \u003e 0.5 g/24 hours. Which of the following correctly describes the cause of her renal condition?","explanation":"**Systemic lupus erythematosus** is a systemic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organs, including the kidneys. The presence of **malar rash**, along with alopecia, photosensitivity, oral ulcers, and proteinuria raises suspicion of SLE.\r\n\r\nLupus nephritis - a common complication of SLE - can cause inflammation and damage to the glomeruli, leading to **proteinuria** and potentially other renal manifestations such as hematuria, decreased kidney function, and hypertension.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 222.","responses":[{"text":"Focal sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Migraine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythmatosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amyloidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21132,"text":"Which of the following is the correct term for the following statement \"Whoever causes a woman with child some of whose limbs or organs have been formed to miscarry, if such miscarriage is not caused in good faith for the purpose of saving the life of the woman\"?","explanation":"**Ishqat-e-janin** is a legal term used to describe the act of **intentionally** causing a **miscarriage** or abortion, which is generally prohibited in many legal systems unless it is performed in good faith to save the life of the pregnant woman.","reference":"Q: What does mean Isqat-i-Janin under PPC? Accessed November 21, 2023. https://pakistanlawyer.com/support/knowledgebase.php?article=762","responses":[{"text":"Ishqat-e-hamal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ikrah-e-tam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Geyer-jaifah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ishqat-e-janin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajah ammah","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21133,"text":"Which of the following is an indication of acute tubular necrosis caused by toxins?","explanation":"**Acute tubular necrosis** refers to a condition in which the renal tubular cells of the kidneys are damaged, often due to the toxic effects of substances like drugs, contrast agents, or toxins. This damage can lead to a decrease in the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which is the rate at which the kidneys filter blood. A **reduced GFR** results in a decrease in the ability of the kidneys to filter and excrete waste products and excess fluids, leading to **oliguria**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIncreased glucose in urine may be seen in conditions like diabetes mellitus.\r\n\r\nAn increase in GFR is not typically seen in ATN.\r\n\r\nPolyuria is not typically a feature of ATN.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 926.","responses":[{"text":"Increased GFR and polyuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased glucose concentration in urine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased GFR and oliguria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced GFR and polyuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased GFR and oliguria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21141,"text":"A person presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of urinary incontinence and burning micturition. After a detailed investigation, a digital rectal examination is performed on which his prostate gland is found to be stony hard. Which of the following can be the most probable diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Prostate adenocarcinoma**, or prostate cancer, often presents with a hard, irregular prostate on digital rectal examination. The description of the prostate as \"stony hard\" is particularly suggestive of malignancy. Prostate cancer can cause urinary symptoms due to its location and the potential for growth into surrounding tissues or structures.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) can cause urinary symptoms like incontinence and burning micturition due to compression of the urethra, the prostate in BPH is typically enlarged and feels smooth, not hard.\r\n\r\nProstatic calcification can occur, but it is usually associated with chronic inflammation or previous infections. A \"stony hard\" prostate and the accompanying symptoms align more closely with carcinoma.\r\n\r\nProstatitis is an inflammation of the prostate, typically resulting in a tender and swollen (but not hard) prostate.","reference":"Leslie, Stephen W., et al. “Prostate Cancer.” StatPearls [Internet], StatPearls Publishing, 2023. www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470550/.","responses":[{"text":"Prostate adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcified prostate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflamed prostate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign prostate hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

